In the margin are written, in a fine and beautiful hand of the early part of the fourteenth century, various glosses and notes. These leaves comprise part os book IX„ ce. 4, 5, 6, 9, 10. These fragments fully confirm ROGER BACON'S condemnation of the medieval Latin versions of the great Stagyrite’s works. Bacon went so far as to advise the burning of all the Latin versions of Aristotle then current, on the ground that it was a loss of time to study them.1 He also asserts that no mortal can truly understand anything from these translations, as his own cxper1ence showcd.2 This is certainly true of the Nottingharn fragments, sor the hypo- thetical cases are stated in the indicative mood, there Is a most bewildering carelessness in the rendering of the particles and de· finitions, and there are blunders that plainly prove that the transcribet· did not understand the work he was copying. Thus substantia means both ‘the subject of the discourse'3 and ‘the being, essence or nature of a thing;’4 per accidens (accidently) translates ‘hypotheti- cally;’ the question whether it was Kleon or Sokrates that came,5 is actually rendered: ‘Et quaestio est, utrum ille veniens cst melion aul forles’!
